value.value: A secondary fiber cell that contains a nucleus.

An elongating cell that rapidly obliterates the lumen of the lens vesicle. Subsequently, differentiation of this cell type at the lens equator leads to the formation of secondary fiber cells that come to overlie the primary fibers.

label.value: light chief cell of parathyroid gland

value.value: A chief cell that is bigger than dark chief cells and has a larger and lighter nucleus and a cytoplasm with few granules.
An epithelial cell of the prostate.
An epithelial cell of prostatic duct.
An epithelial cell of the prostatic acinus.
A cell of the basal layer of the epithelium in the prostatic acinus.
A cell of the luminal layer of the epithelium in the prostatic acinus.

label.value: basal epithelial cell of prostatic duct

value.value: A cell that constitutes the basal layer of epithelium in the prostatic duct.

label.value: luminal epithelial cell of prostatic duct

value.value: A cell that constitutes the luminal layer of epithelium of prostatic duct.
A primordial germ cell that is destined to become a male germ cell.
A primordial cell from which an oocyte (ovum) ultimately is developed.
A fibroblast in the bone marrow.
A fibroblasts found in interstitial spaces in the pulmonary tract. Greater numbers of these cells are found in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis.
A cell containing at least one nucleus.

label.value: smooth muscle cell of sphincter of pupil
Smooth muscle fiber of sphincter of pupil

value.value: A circular smooth muscle cell of the iris, innervated by the ciliary nerves (parasympathetic), and acting to contract the pupil. This muscle cell derives from neuroectoderm. This smooth muscle cell results from transformation of epithelial cells to smooth muscle cells.
A nonstratified squamous cell located in the ectocervix.
A hematopoeitic stem cell found in the blood. Normally found in very limited numbers in the peripheral circulation (less than 0.1% of all nucleated cells).
A tissue macrophage that is in the pleural space.

A pluripotent stem cell has the ability to form cells from all three germ layers (ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm). However, unlike totipotent stem cells, they cell can not generate all the cells of the whole organism such as placenta.
A stem cell that can differentiate into a cardiac myocyte.

label.value: Stem cell of intestinal crypt of Lieberkuhn

value.value: A cell that is found in a zone occupying the bottom region of the crypt; provide the source of most of the cell types of the intestinal epithelium; proliferate by mitotic division; differentiates into columnar or goblet cells.
An epithelial cell of the musculomembranous digestive tube extending from the mouth to the anus.
An epithelial cell of the esophagus.
An epithelial cell of the large intestine.
An epithelial cell of the small intestine.
A stromal cell of the endometrium that is fibroblastic in appearance. During decidualization this cell may differentiate into a decidual stromal cell.
A supportive cell that has characteristics of glial cell. Processes of this cell envelope the junctions between glomus cells and nerve endings.
An epithelial cell of thyroid gland.
A cell type that varies from squamous to columnar, depending on their activity with microvillus directed luminally. This cell produces and secretes thyroid hormones.
The stem cell from which glial precursor cell arises from.
An epithelial cell of the parathyroid gland.
An endothelial cell found in the mucosa associated with the facial skeleton.
An endothelial cell that lines any of the venous cavities through which blood passes in various glands and organs such as the spleen and liver.

One of three types of epithelial cells that populate the parathyroid gland; cytological characteristics intermediate between those of the chief cell and of the oxyphil cell. Because only one hormone is produced, the three cell forms are widely believed to be different phases in the life cycle of a single cell type, with the chief cell being its physiologically active stage.
A type of enteroendocrine cell found in the stomach that secretes glucagon.
A D cell located in the colon.

label.value: type D cell of small intestine

value.value: A type D cell of the small intestine.
A type D cell found in the stomach.
An enteroendocrine cell that stores and secretes Ghrelin.
An endocrine cell that secretes vasoactive intestinal peptide.
A type EC enteroendocrine cell in the duodenum and jejunum that stores and secretes motilin and 5-hydroxytryptamine.
A type EC enteredocrine cell in the intestines that stores and secretes substance P and 5-hydroxytryptamine.
A cell that secretes motilin, a gastric hormone that at low pH inhibits gastric motor activity, whereas at high pH has a stimulating effect.
A type EC enteroendocrine cell type that is numerous in the fundus of the stomach; stores 5-hydroxytryptamine and histamine.
A cell type that secretes histamine.

label.value: Type F cell of pancreatic islet

value.value: A PP cell located in the islets of the pancreas.

definition.value: The term PP cell of pancreatic acinus was obsoleted due to a lack of evidence, making PP cell of pancreatic islets synonymous with pancreatic PP cell.

value.value: An enteroendocrine cell commonest in the duodenum and jejunum, rare in ileum, that secretes cholecystokinin. This cell type is involved in the regulation of digestive enzymes and bile.
An enteroendocrine cell of duodenum and jejunum that produces gastric inhibitory peptide.

A enteroendocrine cell type that is numerous in ileum, present in jejunum and large intestine, few in duodenum. This cell type produces glucagon-like immunoreactants (glicentin, glucagon-37, glucagon-29, GLP-1 and -2) and PYY.
